  <graph edgedefault="undirected">
    <node id="JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX">
      <data key="d0">JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX is a database index object in the HR schema, designed to optimize data retrieval operations on the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, specifically for queries filtering or sorting by the DEPARTMENT_ID column. It is a non-unique, performance-oriented structure with properties such as NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL, and is implemented as a standard B-tree index. The index supports business processes and reporting that require efficient access to job history by department.&lt;SEP&gt;JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX is a non-unique database index created on the DEPARTMENT_ID column of the JOB_HISTORY table in the HR schema. It is designed to improve the performance of department-based queries on job history data, with configuration options such as NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL to optimize for efficient creation and access.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1de866b5986aebcccae444bb76f0105b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f93583342dc27c6c3331c90c22264c1b</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.jhist_department_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753985439</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.JOB_HISTORY">
      <data key="d0">HR.JOB_HISTORY</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.JOB_HISTORY is a database table in the HR schema that stores historical job information for employees, including changes in job roles, departments, and employment periods.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.JOB_HISTORY is a database table within the HR schema that records the historical job assignments of employees. It stores comprehensive information about employee job history, including job transitions, tenure, start and end dates, job roles, and department associations. The table contains references to employees, jobs, and departments, and enforces data integrity through primary and foreign key constraints. HR.JOB_HISTORY is indexed by JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX (for department associations) and HR.JHIST_JOB_IX (for the JOB_ID column), supporting efficient queries, reporting, and analytics. It serves as an audit trail and is frequently used for HR processes, business process support, auditing, and maintaining data integrity related to employee job history.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1de866b5986aebcccae444bb76f0105b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3f5925672172ca41c13261bbb15e276f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f233a5b64c38c0d8b24476f5ade01458&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e24ec303a0c36890649afea58f3fecf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db329f300a48c02eb5236b03367fb951</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.jhist_job_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.jhist_department_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.jhist_employee_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.job_history.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753989799</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPARTMENT_ID">
      <data key="d0">DEPARTMENT_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPARTMENT_ID is a column in the EMPLOYEES table, usually of type NUMBER, representing the department to which an employee belongs. It is the indexed column in EMP_DEPARTMENT_IX and is likely a foreign key to the DEPARTMENTS table.&lt;SEP&gt;DEPARTMENT_ID is a data field (column) in the HR.EMPLOYEES table, representing the department to which each employee belongs. It is the basis for the EMP_DEPARTMENT_IX index.&lt;SEP&gt;DEPARTMENT_ID is a unique identifier assigned to each department, serving as the primary key in the HR.DEPARTMENTS table to ensure that every department is distinctly addressable and to maintain data integrity. This column is referenced by other tables, such as HR.EMPLOYEES and HR.JOB_HISTORY, where it acts as a foreign key linking employees and job history records to their respective departments. In the HR.EMPLOYEES table, DEPARTMENT_ID is an optional column that indicates the department where an employee works, supporting organizational structure, reporting, and budgeting. In the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, DEPARTMENT_ID, typically a numeric or integer type, represents the department associated with a particular job history record and is also an optional field. It is indexed by JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX to optimize queries involving department-based filtering, joining, or sorting. Overall, DEPARTMENT_ID is a key identifier that facilitates data integrity, efficient data retrieval, and the tracking of departmental changes across the HR.DEPARTMENTS, HR.EMPLOYEES, and HR.JOB_HISTORY tables.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1de866b5986aebcccae444bb76f0105b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a837c6cab856c3245b8657e36779634a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3f5925672172ca41c13261bbb15e276f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a41048dcaa5356d2ec9a434224117f92&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2062c94493f296606e14ada3763e1f63&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f233a5b64c38c0d8b24476f5ade01458&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ce17d92986b53e2ccc91df6cade7686&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f93583342dc27c6c3331c90c22264c1b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c702962a1d2dd2ec0da396df20249e50&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a01dcf1c9756eb26a45470d65ee6f338</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.departments.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.job_history.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.jhist_department_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.employees.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.emp_department_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988665</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR">
      <data key="d0">HR</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">HR (Human Resources) refers to both the organizational unit within a company and the corresponding database schema responsible for managing all aspects of employee and workforce data. As a department, HR oversees critical functions such as employee data management, payroll, compensation, hiring, reporting, enforcement of business rules, and data integrity, playing a central role in supporting business processes related to workforce management and organizational structure. In the context of a database, HR is the schema or user that owns essential tables such as EMPLOYEES, DEPARTMENTS, JOB_HISTORY, JOBS, LOCATIONS, and COUNTRIES, as well as other key tables and related data structures. HR also manages important indexes, including EMP_MANAGER_IX, JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX, JHIST_JOB_IX, JHIST_EMPLOYEE_IX, LOC_STATE_PROVINCE_IX, and EMP_DEPARTMENT_IX, which are used to organize, manage, and analyze employee job history, job-related information, department data, and location data. Overall, HR is essential for managing employee-related data and processes, both as a functional department and as a database schema, ensuring the effective administration, integrity, and analysis of human resources within the organization.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ac0843275fead0fc502c43470c04f3a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1de866b5986aebcccae444bb76f0105b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e34db40cf2365e32f299f601d34d886a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf21f34bdc08f5a0331c894d66d1eb31&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9fedc09939f22511bb84ca5aa5751c23&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-60fc3f432e526e12067b6a12ccbff962&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0ca92db0127a6ddd811d5e51df59e9bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3f5925672172ca41c13261bbb15e276f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a41048dcaa5356d2ec9a434224117f92&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-410ac6b3623a033ae62dfa51c383d7a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ce17d92986b53e2ccc91df6cade7686&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e24ec303a0c36890649afea58f3fecf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f93583342dc27c6c3331c90c22264c1b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c702962a1d2dd2ec0da396df20249e50&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bcb6882954ebc0bf73a53009f4e43c91&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a01dcf1c9756eb26a45470d65ee6f338&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db329f300a48c02eb5236b03367fb951</data>
