    <node id="Foreign Key Constraint">
      <data key="d0">Foreign Key Constraint</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Foreign Key Constraint is a database rule that enforces referential integrity and data consistency across multiple tables in a database. In the HR schema, it ensures that COUNTRY_ID values in the LOCATIONS table exist in the COUNTRIES table, supporting data integrity and internationalization. Additionally, it enforces that REGION_ID in the COUNTRIES table references a valid REGION_ID in the REGIONS table, ensuring valid region assignment. In the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, Foreign Key Constraint guarantees that JOB_ID values exist in the JOBS table, and also enforces valid references to HR.EMPLOYEES, HR.JOBS, and HR.DEPARTMENTS. Overall, Foreign Key Constraint plays a crucial role in maintaining accurate and consistent relationships between related tables within the database.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-db329f300a48c02eb5236b03367fb951&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f233a5b64c38c0d8b24476f5ade01458&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73f007da0ab621159b7da01edd3c2d4c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-25b7b3b2770cd1281cfdd6e1a0e9ab43</data>
