    <node id="LOC_CITY_IX">
      <data key="d0">LOC_CITY_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">LOC_CITY_IX is an index object in the hr schema of a database, specifically designed to optimize query performance for operations involving the CITY column in the hr.LOCATIONS table. It is a standard B-tree index created in ascending order on the CITY column, with options such as NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL to control performance, storage, and creation behavior. The index is used to accelerate queries that filter, sort, or join on city names, supporting business scenarios like city-based searches and reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7b4c65c6163252963d56c1f1400c52aa</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753985995</data>
    </node>
    <node id="hr">
      <data key="d0">hr</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The hr schema is an organizational namespace within the database that manages and organizes human resources-related data structures. It contains a variety of tables and views, including employees, departments, jobs, locations, countries, and regions. Specifically, the hr schema owns the LOCATIONS table along with the LOC_CITY_IX and LOC_STATE_PROVINCE_IX indexes, as well as the DEPARTMENTS table and the DEPT_LOCATION_IX index. This schema is typically used for managing human resources or organizational data within an organization's database, representing the Human Resources domain.&lt;SEP&gt;hr is the schema or logical namespace in the database, often representing the Human Resources department or module. It contains tables such as LOCATIONS and indexes such as LOC_COUNTRY_IX.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-51ba69f951ee5b889d1443142c78204b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb684b9b744514893d0d1b99289bbe05&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67ba005b5e6c9ddace0480cb68a9b2f1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7b4c65c6163252963d56c1f1400c52aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8df8c5ab687d9a2ed7300b6dbca3dec</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.emp_details_view.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_city_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_country_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.dept_location_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_state_province_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988800</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Index Creation">
      <data key="d0">Index Creation</data>
      <data key="d1">event</data>
      <data key="d2">Index Creation is the process of building database indexes, such as HR.JHIST_JOB_IX, LOC_CITY_IX, LOC_STATE_PROVINCE_IX, and EMP_NAME_IX. This process often involves specifying various properties to optimize performance and resource usage. Common options used during Index Creation include NOLOGGING, which reduces redo log generation; NOCOMPRESS, which prevents index data compression; and NOPARALLEL, which disables parallel execution during index creation. For example, the LOC_CITY_IX index is built on the CITY column of the hr.LOCATIONS table, while other indexes like LOC_STATE_PROVINCE_IX and EMP_NAME_IX can also be optimized using these options. Overall, Index Creation is a configurable process that allows database administrators to tailor index building to specific requirements and system constraints.&lt;SEP&gt;Index creation is the process of building an index such as LOC_COUNTRY_IX, which may involve options like NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL.&lt;SEP&gt;Index Creation is the process of building the JHIST_EMPLOYEE_IX index on the JOB_HISTORY table, involving properties such as NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-51ba69f951ee5b889d1443142c78204b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb684b9b744514893d0d1b99289bbe05&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0ca92db0127a6ddd811d5e51df59e9bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-60fc3f432e526e12067b6a12ccbff962&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7b4c65c6163252963d56c1f1400c52aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db329f300a48c02eb5236b03367fb951</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.jhist_job_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_state_province_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.jhist_employee_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_country_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.emp_name_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753989766</data>
    </node>
