      <data key="d0">query optimizer</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The query optimizer is a database component responsible for determining the most efficient way to execute a query, often leveraging indexes such as hr.LOC_CITY_IX to improve performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a2423bebf79f4b25a5ba6899782bf512</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986015</data>
    </node>
    <node id="business processes">
      <data key="d0">business processes</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Business processes are organizational workflows that rely on efficient access to department data, often utilizing the DEPT_LOCATION_IX index for performance.&lt;SEP&gt;Business processes refer to the operational activities within an organization that require frequent access to location data, particularly by city, and benefit from the performance improvements provided by the hr.LOC_CITY_IX index.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7caa66c20d092a335dc8648173fb5354&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a2423bebf79f4b25a5ba6899782bf512</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.dept_location_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988164</data>
    </node>
    <node id="production environments">
      <data key="d0">production environments</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Production environments are live operational settings where database reliability and recoverability are critical. Enabling logging is recommended in these environments to ensure data recoverability.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a2423bebf79f4b25a5ba6899782bf512</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986015</data>
    </node>
    <node id="large data modifications">
      <data key="d0">large data modifications</data>
      <data key="d1">event</data>
      <data key="d2">Large data modifications refer to significant changes in the data stored in the hr.LOCATIONS table, which can impact the performance and effectiveness of the hr.LOC_CITY_IX index, necessitating periodic rebuilding or analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a2423bebf79f4b25a5ba6899782bf512</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986016</data>
    </node>
    <node id="index creation">
      <data key="d0">index creation</data>
      <data key="d1">event</data>
      <data key="d2">Index creation is the process of building the DEPT_LOCATION_IX index on the hr.DEPARTMENTS table, with specific options such as NOLOGGING and NOCOMPRESS.&lt;SEP&gt;Index creation is the process of building the hr.LOC_CITY_IX index on the CITY column of the hr.LOCATIONS table, with specific settings such as NOCOMPRESS and NOLOGGING to optimize for speed and storage.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e8df8c5ab687d9a2ed7300b6dbca3dec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a2423bebf79f4b25a5ba6899782bf512</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.dept_location_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988152</data>
    </node>
    <node id="storage consumption">
      <data key="d0">storage consumption</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Storage consumption refers to the amount of storage space used by the hr.LOC_CITY_IX index, which can be affected by the NOCOMPRESS setting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a2423bebf79f4b25a5ba6899782bf512</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986016</data>
    </node>
    <node id="recoverability">
      <data key="d0">recoverability</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Recoverability is the ability to restore the database or index to a consistent state after a failure. It is impacted by the NOLOGGING setting during index creation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a2423bebf79f4b25a5ba6899782bf512</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.loc_city_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986017</data>
    </node>
    <node id="hr.REGIONS Table">
      <data key="d0">hr.REGIONS Table</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The hr.REGIONS table is a core reference table within the Human Resources (HR) schema of a business database. It catalogs different geographical regions relevant to the organization, serving as a foundational lookup for other location-based entities such as countries and locations. It is used for organizing, grouping, and segmenting business data by region, supporting reporting, analytics, and business process segmentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986143</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REGION_ID">
      <data key="d0">REGION_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">REGION_ID is a numeric column that plays a key role in both the HR.COUNTRIES and HR.REGIONS tables. In the HR.REGIONS table, REGION_ID serves as the primary key, uniquely identifying each region, is not nullable, and is used for efficient lookup and joining with other tables. In the HR.COUNTRIES table, REGION_ID is a column that acts as a foreign key referencing the REGION_ID in the HR.REGIONS table. This relationship enables the assignment of countries to specific regions, supports hierarchical geographic data, and ensures referential integrity. In the HR.COUNTRIES table, REGION_ID is optional (nullable), allowing for countries that may not be assigned to a region.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e34db40cf2365e32f299f601d34d886a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73f007da0ab621159b7da01edd3c2d4c</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.countries.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988950</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REGION_NAME">
      <data key="d0">REGION_NAME</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">REGION_NAME is a variable-length character column in the hr.REGIONS table that stores the human-readable name of each region. It is optional (nullable) and provides descriptive information for each region.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986143</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Human Resources (HR) Schema">
      <data key="d0">Human Resources (HR) Schema</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The Human Resources (HR) schema is a logical grouping of tables and objects in a business database, focused on managing employee, location, and organizational data. The hr.REGIONS table is part of this schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986143</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Geographical Region">
      <data key="d0">Geographical Region</data>
      <data key="d1">geo</data>
      <data key="d2">A geographical region, as represented in the hr.REGIONS table, is a defined area used by the organization to group countries and locations for business, reporting, and analytical purposes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986143</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REG_ID_PK">
      <data key="d0">REG_ID_PK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The primary key constraint on the REGION_ID column in the hr.REGIONS table, enforcing uniqueness and non-nullability for each region record.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986143</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Location">
      <data key="d0">Location</data>
      <data key="d1">geo</data>
      <data key="d2">A Location represents the physical place where a department is situated. In the HR schema, each Location is identified by a LOCATION_ID and is recorded in the LOCATIONS table, which includes attributes such as location_id, city, state_province, and country_id. Locations are grouped under a country and region, and are associated with regions via the LOCATIONS table. Not all departments are required to have a fixed location, but when they do, the Location serves as the link between the department, its country, and its region.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2062c94493f296606e14ada3763e1f63&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89893c024eb2366461dff72cd763aa91&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67ba005b5e6c9ddace0480cb68a9b2f1</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.emp_details_view.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.departments.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753987876</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Business Process Segmentation">
      <data key="d0">Business Process Segmentation</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The division of business processes by region, enabled by the hr.REGIONS table for organizational and analytical purposes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Master Data Management">
      <data key="d0">Master Data Management</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A business process that uses the hr.REGIONS table to maintain a consistent and accurate list of regions for geographic segmentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Hierarchical Location Mapping">
      <data key="d0">Hierarchical Location Mapping</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A data structure where regions are at the top level, followed by countries and then locations, supported by the hr.REGIONS table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Placeholder Region Record">
      <data key="d0">Placeholder Region Record</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A region record in the hr.REGIONS table that may lack a REGION_NAME, used for placeholder or legacy data purposes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b690355f198c13b5e87d1ffcca55ecdb</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986151</data>
    </node>
    <node id="hr.REGIONS table">
      <data key="d0">hr.REGIONS table</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The hr.REGIONS table is a foundational reference table within the HR schema of a database, used to manage and segment geographic regions. It enforces data integrity with a primary key, supports business processes such as reporting and analytics by region, and integrates with other tables like COUNTRIES and LOCATIONS. The table is small, requires minimal maintenance, and is designed for efficient access and integration in HR applications.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986151</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR schema">
      <data key="d0">HR schema</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The HR schema is a database schema that organizes and manages human resources data, including tables such as HR.JOBS, employee, and job history tables. It supports HR business processes and ensures data consistency and reliability.&lt;SEP&gt;The HR schema is a logical grouping within a database that organizes human resources-related data, including tables for employees, offices, regions, countries, and locations. It provides structure and context for HR data management and reporting.&lt;SEP&gt;The overall database schema that organizes and manages human resources data, including departments, employees, and locations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2e8912ac03211e6d10a671c1a31ccb8e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a837c6cab856c3245b8657e36779634a</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.departments.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.jobs.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753989405</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUNTRIES table">
      <data key="d0">COUNTRIES table</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The COUNTRIES table is a related reference table within the HR schema, used to store information about countries and often joined with the REGIONS table for geographic segmentation and reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986151</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOCATIONS table">
      <data key="d0">LOCATIONS table</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The LOCATIONS table is a referenced database entity that stores valid location records for departments. It ensures that each department's location is valid and exists, supporting referential integrity in the HR schema.&lt;SEP&gt;The LOCATIONS table is another related table in the HR schema, containing data about specific office or work locations, and is commonly joined with the REGIONS table for filtering and aggregation by region.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a837c6cab856c3245b8657e36779634a</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.departments.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753987890</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Geographic region">
      <data key="d0">Geographic region</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A geographic region represents a defined area or segment used for organizing, filtering, and reporting HR data such as employees and offices. Regions are managed and referenced through the hr.REGIONS table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Employees">
      <data key="d0">Employees</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Employees are individuals whose HR data (such as location, region, and office) is managed within the HR schema and can be filtered or grouped by region using the hr.REGIONS table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Offices">
      <data key="d0">Offices</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Offices are physical or organizational locations where employees work, and their data is managed within the HR schema, often associated with regions for reporting and analytics.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Master data management">
      <data key="d0">Master data management</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A set of processes and tools for managing core business data, such as geographic regions, to ensure consistency and accuracy across the organization.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Location hierarchy">
      <data key="d0">Location hierarchy</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A structured organization of locations (regions, countries, offices) used for data integration, reporting, and filtering in HR systems.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Application dropdowns">
      <data key="d0">Application dropdowns</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">User interface elements in HR applications that allow users to select regions, countries, or locations for filtering or reporting purposes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Filters">
      <data key="d0">Filters</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Mechanisms in HR applications or reports that allow users to narrow down data by region, country, or location.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Reporting modules">
      <data key="d0">Reporting modules</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Components of HR applications that generate reports, often using region, country, or location as grouping or filtering criteria.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Primary key">
      <data key="d0">Primary key</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A unique identifier for each record in the hr.REGIONS table, ensuring data integrity and efficient access.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986155</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Table index">
      <data key="d0">Table index</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A database structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on the hr.REGIONS table, particularly by REGION_ID.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986155</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Maintenance">
      <data key="d0">Maintenance</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Regular review and validation of the HR.DEPARTMENTS table, including orphaned departments and referential integrity checks.&lt;SEP&gt;The ongoing process of updating the hr.REGIONS table, such as adding or renaming regions, which is minimal due to the table's small size.&lt;SEP&gt;The process of reviewing and updating the view if base table structures change, and monitoring performance as data grows.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89893c024eb2366461dff72cd763aa91&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a837c6cab856c3245b8657e36779634a</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.emp_details_view.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.departments.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753987900</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Business processes">
      <data key="d0">Business processes</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Organizational activities supported by the hr.REGIONS table, such as reporting, analytics, and geographic segmentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986155</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Selection">
      <data key="d0">Selection</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The process of choosing a region from a list, often in application dropdowns or reports.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986155</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Join">
      <data key="d0">Join</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A database operation that combines data from the hr.REGIONS table with other tables like COUNTRIES or LOCATIONS for aggregation or filtering.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986158</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Aggregation">
      <data key="d0">Aggregation</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The process of summarizing HR data by region, enabled by joining the hr.REGIONS table with other tables.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986158</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Filtering">
      <data key="d0">Filtering</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The process of narrowing down HR data by region, enabled by the hr.REGIONS table and its integration with other tables.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-44183b0ee98213bcef211e8d83f1b64d</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.regions.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986158</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.JHIST_JOB_IX">
      <data key="d0">HR.JHIST_JOB_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.JHIST_JOB_IX is a non-unique, single-column B-tree index in the HR schema of a database. It is created on the JOB_ID column of the HR.JOB_HISTORY table to optimize query performance for operations filtering, joining, or sorting data based on JOB_ID. The index uses NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL properties, and is primarily intended to accelerate business processes and analytics involving job history records.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.JHIST_JOB_IX is a standard, non-unique B-tree index created on the JOB_ID column of the JOB_HISTORY table. It is designed to optimize query performance for job-based lookups and reporting within the HR database schema. The index uses NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL settings, focusing on efficient creation and straightforward maintenance, and does not employ advanced features such as bitmap or partitioning.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-bcb6882954ebc0bf73a53009f4e43c91&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db329f300a48c02eb5236b03367fb951</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.jhist_job_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753986430</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Application Modules">
      <data key="d0">Application Modules</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Application Modules are software components or systems, typically part of HR systems, that display, analyze, or process employee job history by interacting with the HR.JOB_HISTORY table. They often leverage the HR.JHIST_JOB_IX index to efficiently retrieve, display, or analyze job history data, relying on the integrity and structure of the HR.JOB_HISTORY table. Additionally, Application Modules may use the LOC_STATE_PROVINCE_IX index to filter or search locations by state or province, enhancing their ability to manage and present HR-related information effectively.&lt;SEP&gt;Application modules refer to software components that display or manage employees within departments, utilizing the EMP_DEPARTMENT_IX index to optimize performance for department-based operations.&lt;SEP&gt;Application modules are software components or systems that display or process location data by country, relying on the performance benefits of LOC_COUNTRY_IX.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-51ba69f951ee5b889d1443142c78204b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb684b9b744514893d0d1b99289bbe05&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f233a5b64c38c0d8b24476f5ade01458&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bcb6882954ebc0bf73a53009f4e43c91&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a01dcf1c9756eb26a45470d65ee6f338&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db329f300a48c02eb5236b03367fb951</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.jhist_job_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.job_history.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_country_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.emp_department_ix.md&lt;SEP&gt;hr.loc_state_province_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988809</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ETL Processes">
      <data key="d0">ETL Processes</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) processes are data integration workflows that may load or synchronize location data, leveraging the LOC_COUNTRY_IX index for efficient data access.&lt;SEP&gt;ETL Processes (Extract, Transform, Load) are data integration workflows that load or transform job history data for analytics, reporting, or other downstream applications.&lt;SEP&gt;ETL Processes (Extract, Transform, Load) are data integration workflows that load or transform job history data, potentially benefiting from the HR.JHIST_JOB_IX index for efficient data access.</data>
