    <node id="Geo">
      <data key="d0">Geo</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Represents the geographical aspect of department locations, as referenced by LOCATION_ID and the LOCATIONS table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a837c6cab856c3245b8657e36779634a</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.departments.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753987902</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPT_LOCATION_IX">
      <data key="d0">DEPT_LOCATION_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPT_LOCATION_IX is a database index on the LOCATION_ID column of the hr.DEPARTMENTS table. It is a standard, non-unique B-tree index designed to optimize performance for location-based queries. The index is configured with NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL options, making it suitable for environments prioritizing fast data access and efficient bulk operations over storage savings and full recoverability.&lt;SEP&gt;DEPT_LOCATION_IX is a standard, non-unique B-tree index in the Oracle database, created on the LOCATION_ID column of the hr.DEPARTMENTS table. Its primary purpose is to optimize data retrieval for queries filtering, joining, or sorting by department location. The index is configured with NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL options, prioritizing performance for bulk operations and large data loads over storage savings and full recoverability.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7caa66c20d092a335dc8648173fb5354&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8df8c5ab687d9a2ed7300b6dbca3dec</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.dept_location_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="hr.DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d0">hr.DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">hr.DEPARTMENTS is a database table within the hr schema, representing organizational departments. It contains information about each department, including its associated location, and is the primary table indexed by DEPT_LOCATION_IX.&lt;SEP&gt;hr.DEPARTMENTS is a database table, likely part of a human resources schema, that stores information about departments, including their associated LOCATION_ID.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7caa66c20d092a335dc8648173fb5354&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8df8c5ab687d9a2ed7300b6dbca3dec</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.dept_location_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="location-based queries">
      <data key="d0">location-based queries</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Location-based queries are database operations that filter, join, or sort department records based on their LOCATION_ID. These queries benefit from the presence of the DEPT_LOCATION_IX index for improved performance.&lt;SEP&gt;Location-based queries refer to database queries that filter or retrieve data based on the LOCATION_ID field, enabling efficient access to department data by location.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7caa66c20d092a335dc8648173fb5354&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8df8c5ab687d9a2ed7300b6dbca3dec</data>
      <data key="d4">hr.dept_location_ix.md</data>
      <data key="d5">1753988145</data>
    </node>
